latestPosts.caption:
I honestly don’t understand what’s going on with all these people spreading negativity about the vegan lifestyle. Some say it’s bad, or call it propaganda, and insist that people shouldn’t go vegan. Every time I hear that, it’s genuinely heart-wrenching. I just want to ask them—have you even thought about what you’re saying?
There’s a reason why more and more people are choosing to go vegan. It’s not just a trend—it’s a conscious shift. People are doing it for the animals, for the environment, and for their own health. The compassion behind it, the ethical foundation—it’s powerful.
And then there’s the argument that a vegan diet is expensive or lacks protein. That’s just misinformation. I’ve been vegan for over a year now, and I’m fit, healthy, and lifting heavy in the gym. I have energy, I recover well, and I’m thriving. You don’t need animal products to get strong or stay healthy.
There’s a vast variety of plant-based foods out there—beans, lentils, tofu, tempeh, whole grains, nuts, seeds, and more. I create balanced diets for others without using any supplements, and they still hit great protein targets. But if someone does want a protein boost, there are affordable plant-based protein powders out there—often cheaper than whey and much easier on the body.
The idea that plant-based eating is only for the rich is just another myth. Once you actually try it and understand it, you’ll realize it’s not only doable, but sustainable, nourishing, and even soulful. You don’t need fancy superfoods or expensive brands—you just need good intentions and the will to explore.
I encourage everyone to stop listening blindly to what people say. Read more, watch insightful content, and follow people who actually know what they’re talking about—not just random insta stars but truly informed voices in the space. Some of the people I look up to are…
@nimai_delgado @richroll @michaelgregermd 
Stay positive, stay compassionate, and stay informed. The vegan lifestyle isn’t just about food—it’s about living in alignment with your values and making choices that benefit all living beings.
